title: FPV camera box fatshark or other cameras

description.text:
Many FPV camera kits come as components - transmitter, camera, battery filter, etc; I wanted a box to put it all inside, so the box could be rubber-banded/fixed onto various things without actually being part of those things. In this case, big robot car/tank thing, but use as you see fit :)

There is enough space for common 3 cell LiPo batteries or others; there is dividers to stop the battery from sliding around. Theres space and cutout for FPV camera and lens, and cutout for transmitter antenna.

Compartments can fit LiPo battery beeper or other accessories.

description.text:
A simple hatching egg design.

The base and the top part are printed separately.
I used supports for the bottom of the parts in order to avoid issues with overhangs and improve adhesion to the build plate. If you want the egg to stand upright by itself, just don't remove the supports of the base part.

I have uploaded a screenshot of my support setting but you may need to tweak them according to you printer.

Please note that the bird which can be seen on the photo is not a part of this design. You can put inside anything you want :)

You will need to rotate the models on the build plate prior to starting the print. Sorry for that :)

This is a simple but elegant little heart shaped box for Valentine's Day. Fill it with candy, jewelry or anything your Valentine likes and it's sure to be a hit!  
The cut-out hearts in the lid show the contents or print the lid insert in a complimentary or contrasting color for a little "pop"!  
The box is 3-1/3" / 85mm tall and 3/4" / 20mm tall.

The box is printed in two parts - a base and a lid. I like to print the lid with no skin/shell so the fill pattern shows through. This gives an interesting design element. The insert is simply a thin heart that you can print in a complimentary or contrasting color and insert in the lid. It will be seen through the cut out hearts and the open fill pattern. I like to print the insert in clear/white transparent PLA, it looks great showing through red.  
You'll want to finagle your perimeter settings so the four small hearts in the center are "connected". My nozzle is .4mm and I used 4 perimeters. This gives a nice border around these little hearts and the box top itself.  
The darker red one is a wine color PLA. You can mix and match tops and bases. Try combinations of red, wine, pink, white, and transparent!

description.text: This is my first trail hope you like it

print_settings.Notes:: Can be printed on the Select Mini. I went slow at 30mm/sec, using PETG. The design will probably only work for 0.4 nozzles, because the walls are rather thin.

description.text:
I was never really happy with the print bed on my Select Mini. It was sagging in the middle and bent in other places. Getting PETG to stick was always a gamble and high prints regularly popped off near the end. However I didn't want a regular glass sheet because they tend to break all the time. I couldn't get an exactly matching borosilicate plate and having one cut would have been too expensive. So I bought the cheapest small borosilicate bed I could find in China and decided to design my own clamps. As you can see, the height adjustment screws are accessible but the problem is positive overlap on the sides and negative overlap front and back.

Using threaded rods and printed clips, my bed is now rock-solid and sits exactly where I want it. It does not move even when ripping off large prints. In the scad file you can adjust the glass dimensions, the offset from the front of the aluminum plate and select different types of fixings. There is a tiny bit of overhang on the clips to press down the plate. It doesn't collide with the nozzle on an unmodified Mini. I am using an E3DV6 lite (see below), so in my case I had to glue a little spacer (about 2mm) to the inside of the Y carriage where it hits the endstop.

The provided stl file is set up for a 140x140x3mm sheet exactly like mine. You need 4x M4 nuts in the front (I use 2x M4 nylon locking nuts facing outward) and 2x M4 nuts + washers in the back, as well as 2x 180mm M4 threaded rod. The design allows levelling the bed within limits (about 1 mm clearance in my case). You could add printed hand screws in the front or back for easier removal (should be doable without reprinting the clips), but I haven't felt the need yet.
With a shot of hairspray every now and then I never have problems getting PLA or PETG to stick. It is now basically a "press-start-and-go-do-something-else" kind of printer.

Don't forget the spacer for the Z limit switch. I use this, set to 3mm: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1808029
This is the hotend adapter I use with my E3DV6 lite:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1835673

EDIT: Removed a bug in the .scad file pointed out by Pete. Please use the fixed file if you want to play around.

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.175

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Can be printed on the Select Mini. I went slow at 30mm/sec, using PETG. The design will probably only work for 0.4 nozzles, because the walls are rather thin.

comments.text: I am printing this out (for the rest of the week, man, slow!). I did the barrel and I sanded it really smooth. I use 120 grit sandpaper to get rid of the layer lines, and 400 grit to make it smooth. You can also, after that, wet sand with the 400 grit after that to get that extra level of smoothness. Another thing you can do is to use filler primer, which is a spray primer that is similar to the ones you use on minis, but thicker. This fills in the gaps between layer, and means less actual plastic is lost when sanding. You need to do a few coats. .

A French Cleat is a method of holding tools by pairing two 45 degree angles together. A lot of people use Pegboards for the same purpose but many of us prefer the French Cleat design instead as it can hold significantly more weight.

title: Headphone Holder Stand with Cabinet / Shelf
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a headphone stand, printed in 3 pieces on an Anet A8. It is surprisingly sturdy and has virtually zero flex when things are places or moved around. It has cable management holes aswell so you can charge your phone, battery pack, or headphone with style and organization. It has been sanded, painted, and clear coated.

A prototype was made out of legos prior to designing and printing.
You may notice in the model that there it a holder that passes through the cabinet and the holder area. This was for a bolt that i used to connect the two pieces together. If you print this as one piece, you can ignore it.

Post Print :

After printing, I sanded it, painted it with matte paint, then put two layers of clear coat.

Design Process

I had built a headphone stand out of legos that could hold various items, including my battery charger, earbuds, headphones, and cables. I wanted a more elegant solution so I made this.

title: Clip-on pots (with suction cup)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Clip-on pots suitable for clipping over dividers such as glass dividers up to 6mm thick. The pot also includes a recess for an optional suction cup, for example if used in motorhomes (RVs) or caravans.

The pot is in two parts to allow for simple printing with a flat, watertight base and without the need for support of the clip 'handle'. This also means you can pick your own colour combinations even on a single-extruder printer.

For the clip part you can choose the plain or "latticed" version for something (slightly) more arty.

Total size: 121mm tall, 122mm diameter.

(N.B. for a shorter pot, simply tell your slicing program to stop at your required height on the bowl part - once you're at least 5mm clear of the recessed part).

Please don't forget to come back and publish your prints on Thingiverse! I'd love to see what you do with them

Printer:

RepRapPro Ormerod 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

20%

This item is printed in two parts and, whilst it should be a nice tight fit, will need glue to hold it together properly. The clip part has a thin wall which should fit inside the bowl part.

First use a sharp knife and carefully trim flush any blobs of plastic left behind by the layer start point on both the clip side and the inside top of the bowl.

Next do a dry run to make sure the two parts fit nicely and to align the clip 'handle' with the recessed part where the suction cup can go. It may be worthwhile marking the position of the two parts with a pencil somewhere concealed (i.e. under the clip handle).

Take apart again and apply a thin layer of suitable glue to the outside of the thin wall on the bottom of the clip part. Now put back together, and carefully wipe away any excess glue. Place a flat, heavy book on top to hold everything in place while the glue dries.

If you want to add the suction cup, trim the clip parts off a plastic suction cup to leave a flush back and glue this centrally to the recessed area on the bowl. If the suction cups has a little tab to ease removal, align that to face down so you can easily get at it.

I create a series of prefabricated 3D printed constructors. The goal of the project is the development of 3D printing for educational purposes. The model is modeled in the Fusion 360 program.
The printing material is white PLA. The reason for choosing the material is simple:

  • low shrinkage. And since the elements of the designer should fit together without fitting, shrinkage is the most important factor.
  • Excellent adhesion. Since the gun itself is printed standing upright, a good adhesion of a small area is extremely important. However, you can still print only with the raft.
  • Safe. The constructor should be safe, where without it.

The advantage of printed constructs is obvious.

  • Low-cost price
  • you can select the desired scale
  • a fascinating process of printing and assembling the designer.

The cannon consists of eight parts. You can collect it both on glue and without it. To paint details (if there is a desire) it is desirable to still in the disassembled kind.

If anyone is interested I used a printer called Anet A8 Desktop 3D Printer Prusa i3 DIY Kit. (https://goo.gl/XRZlCO).

This fidget spinner uses tungsten for its weights and a ceramic bearing.

Why tungsten? With the exception of gold, tungsten's density is the highest available. Simply put, if you had two identically sized rings, one steel and one tungsten, the tungsten one would weigh 2.4 times more than the steel one. This makes tungsten the perfect material for weighting a fidget spinner!

Why Ceramic? Since I was investing the money in the tungsten, I figured I'd get the fastest bearing I could find. Ceramic bearings last longer, are smoother, and faster than conventional bearings.

Tungsten Weights: http://a.co/b86QjKy
Ceramic Bearing: http://a.co/7rGRu5U

I've made quite a few fidget spinners, and this is by far the fastest and funnest one yet. Tungsten truly makes a huge difference!

The spinner cap is designed for use with an M3x10mm Cap Screw and nut, however, it is not necessary. The caps are a pressure fit and once installed will not fall out.

title: Bike handle phone mount 36mm diameter [Update for GoPro screws]

description.text:
Update to my original design to support GoPro screws.
I adjusted the depth of the two large plates to make them the perfect size to fit a GoPro screw and I added the hexagonal ring to put the small metal piece into that you can find on almost any of the GoPro modules.

You can edit this file and ungroup this thing to ungroup the holes, hexagons and the camera screw if you want to make adjustments for the type of screw or if you want to change the size to fit your handlebar and to keep the size of the camera screw.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/iCw1jDxH53r

description.text:
Simple shell deflector for my SKS Simonov made by Norinco.
Like every SKS owner, there is a Huge problem if you want to mount a sight scope:
The expelled shell will bump in the scope and it can seriously damage it.
With this simple deflector you can avoid such a horrible thing.
Stick it to the left side of the receiver with super strong double sided tape.

remixed_from.author: OnShape
remixed_from.title: Screwdriver Handle for 1/4" magnetic extension bit holder

description.text:
EDIT: the automaticly rendered thumbnail of the *.scad file misses the handle because the thingyverse implementation of that can't import STL files.

Just a quick modification to the Handle made by OnShape.
My opinion is always "do not reinvent the wheel", so I took their handle design and just changed it a bit to make it suitable to insert other types of stuff, like in my example for a veroboard cutter drill bits.

Included is the Openscad script, you would need the original STL (included, named "Screwdriver_Handle.stl") in the same directory than the script. Also included is a modified version with a 3mm hole that I needed for my veroboard cutter (the finished product is in the picture).

In the script, there are five options you can change:

scale_handle_diameter = 0.5;
Determines the diameter, I wanted a small one so I halved the size.
scale_handle_length = 1.0;
same as above just for the length.
hole_diameter = 3.0;
the diameter of the hole in millimeters
hole_depth = 50;
the depth of the hole, also in millimeters
$fn = 32;
If you need a hexagonal shape, change this to 6 (or 3 for a triangle shape etc.)

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

vary, see notes

Notes:

printed with PLA and a fair amount of Z Wobble ;)

Three outlines,
First part with the hole was printed with 50% infill honeycomb,
Second part was printed with 20% fast honeycomb,
Third part (the upper ~1cm) was printed with 40% rectilinear.

But that was just for experimenting (It's actually pretty sturdy, I can't break it with my hands)

title: Support Plateau Réglable Renforcé pour Dagoma DE200

description.text:
Update :

  • 20170715 : Nouvelle version V2 des molettes et du petit outil pour les ajuster. À imprimer en 0.1 (ou le plus finement que vous pouvez) ATTENTION !!! PAS ENCORE TESTÉ !!! Si vous voulez tester vous même c'est au pire 3g de plastique et pas très long à imprimer, n'oubliez pas de partager vos résultats ;) Je testerai moi-même début de semaine prochaine.

Supports pour monter le plateau sur ressorts, avec renfort central (qui permet de contrer les éventuelles faiblesses engendrées du fait du rehaussement du plateau sur longues vis, et ainsi de garder un chariot bien rigide comme un seul bloc).

Les molettes permettent de régler la hauteur sans devoir enlever le revêtement du plateau pour accéder aux vis (un petit outil permet de les tourner facilement - en effet elles sont trop dures pour pouvoir les tourner confortablement aux doigts). (NB: une version améliorée de la molette et de l'outil arriveront bientôt)

Deux canaux sont prévus à chaque emplacement de roulement pour passer un collier plastique afin de prévenir tout jeu à ce niveau là. (Pour bien serrer les colliers, avec une petite pince plate faire une rotation en tirant le collier).

Utilisez des vis M3x25mm tête fraisée ou plus long si vous trouvez, et des écrous nylstop. Comme ressorts j'ai utilisé des vieux que j'avais depuis trèèèès longtemps - diamètre 18mm - privilégiez des bien balaises pour garantir la rigidité.

Si jamais la vis tourne en même temps que la molette, rajoutez un écrou nylstop à la base de la vis juste après la barrette contre le plateau.

Travail inspiré des efforts de Yean Maj (un énorme merci pour les vis) et Pierre-Henry Barbe (le fichier PHB_BarrettePlateauReglable.stl est directement repris de sa création).
Un grand merci à eux deux :)

Pierre Henry Barbe : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2124817

Je n'ai pour l'instant pas mis de vis pour fixer le renfort central aux supports, et à priori vu que ça s'emboîte très bien ça ne bouge pas et je n'en aurai pas besoin. Les emplacement sont là si besoin est d'en mettre (dites moi ce que vous en pensez, si vous en avez mis ou pas et comment ça tient chez vous :). La seule petite chose que je vais améliorer est comme dit ci-dessus les molettes, dont je vais changer la forme des "créneaux" pour qu'elles soient plus faciles à tourner avec l'outil. author: gmarsh23

title: Closed loop air filtration based on EN148 filters

description.text:
As I print a lot I really wanted a solution to keep things healthy.
I print a lot of ABS and this ABS emits fumes and fine dust, both things you don't want in your lungs.
I choose EN148 filters because they are meant to protect our lungs when used in their normal setup (you screw these to face masks, when spray painting, brazing etc.)

I did not have a lot of equipment to test this but:
When using dimafix spray for bed adhesion TVOC values (I have this air quality meter) go up (a lot) inside the printer enclosure.
With a double P3 filter for particles and an AX filter for gasses I was able to lower tvoc to almost normal levels.
As the filter is capable of this I assume the fine dust is also filtered out, I don't know this for sure as I do not have a fine dust meter capable of measuring those things reliably.
I actually have two of these, one is dual P3 + AX, the other one is dual P3 + A2B2.
This to filter as much as possible, I am fairly confident the thing works.
Do note, in order to get some airflow over the filters you should have a fan capable of high static pressure, and not those things for pc cases, I tried several fans and the only fan capable of getting any flow was the Sanyo Denki San Ace 9HV0812P1G001.
Keep in mind that the holes for the wires should be sealed, I used Super glue, this caused the white effect on the abs (see picture).
I had a PWM circuit for it but I wouldn't bother with that, they need to run at full speed to be effective.
The whole thing is assembled with M4 threaded rods,nuts and washers.

Some things I noticed:
-Dust always seemed to stick to my hot end fan, this is much less the case with these filters on.
-Having filters on both sides of the fan decreases the noise a lot.
-I had best performance with the P3 before the fan and then blowing the air out over the gas filter.
-The whole thing is loud, not extremely loud but still but for a desktop printer situation it may be too loud (it can be distracting).
-Sprays for bed adhesion are not that healthy tvoc wise, read the instuctions.

Any questions or remarks, please ask

Make sure your read this, http://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/acs.est.5b04983
I also want to thank Brent Stephens and many others in helping me come up with a working solution.

title: Reusable Apple Mighty Mouse bottom ring
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Everybody who owns one knows how annoying cleaning a Mighty Mouse is. The only way to properly get it working again (for a longer period) is to disassemble it and to clean the internals of the mouse ball "module".

That unfortunately means you have to remove the bottom ring, which is glued on. You can get this thing off without breaking it, but once you've got everything nice and shiny inside, you'll have to glue it back on, because there are no clips to hold it in place.

Enter Thingiverse: rbuckbailey's "Apple Mighty Mouse Replacement Bottom Ring"

I really liked his idea of adding clips to the ring that attach to the "hinges"! This way you can always pry it off, clean the internals and pop the ring right back on. After printing it, I felt the fitment could need a little tweaking, which is why I created my own version in openSCAD. :)

title: ParkZone Wildcat replacement motor mount, Battery box and firewall wedge

description.text:
This is a replacement motor mount for a ParkZone Wildcat. This part is no longer made by the OEM and since hard landings tend to break the original, replacements are needed to keep the many planes out there flying. This part will match the original easily. It can also be remixed to adapt larger motors with offset mounting holes. I will work on that and try to revise the files with an offset mounting hole file.

The file printed just fine without rafts or supports since it is solid. The motor mount holes are inset into the mount leaving only 3mm so that the regular motor mounting bolts will work. As can be seen in the photos the mount is a direct replacement for the stock mount.

The battery box was intended for a replacement after a crash where the stock one is destroyed.

The firewall wedge is for after a crash in which the firewall is destroyed and a flat ply plate is installed. This wedge will give the stock down and right thrust angle for the motor mount. I matches the stock angles exactly.

Prints very well for me. I used Amazon PLA at 210 deg with a heated build plate at 60 deg at .1mm. No supports needed.

title: X Carriage Assembly for Mendelmax 1.5 with LM10UU Bearings

description.text:
This is my design for an X carriage and extruder for my mendelmax 1.5. I designed it in Fusion 360 and it's available here: http://a360.co/2rOfTfF

It's obviously a remix of a Greg Wade's extruder (specifically the Jonas Kueling reloaded) but the orifices are sized specifically to fit a E3D V6 All Metal Extruder. Cut the PTFE tube so that it extends up all the way through the extruder and ends just below the hobbed bolt. There is also a retainer that fits snugly in the heatsink groove and then bolts to the bottom of the extruder with 2 M4 screws and nuts. The extruder screws to the carriage with 2 M3 screws and nuts. For the idler bearing I simply used Jonas Kuehling's excellent design located here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18379/#files It is the one labeled "jonasKueling_gregs-wade-v3_idler-only.stl"

The x carriage includes a mount for a 40mm cooling fan and is spec'd for 3 LM10UU linear bearings. The bearings should snap in pretty tight but if there is any play you can also zip tie them down. I zip tied mine just for extra security.

Printer:

Mendelmax 1.5

No

Notes:

Fusion 360 doesn't give you a lot of choice on the orientation of your exported STL's so you will need to orient the extruder and e3dv6 retainer in your slicer so that the flat side is down on the bed. For the extruder, that is the side that includes the motor mount.

title: Modular tile system for organizing board game tokens

description.text: The reconstruction of a modular tile system for board game tokens organization as it is seen on Kickstarter. The system now consists of 7 square and one dice tray with magnets that can be arranged in a plenty of ways allowing to organize any board game component like cards, tokens, golds and much more.

Printer:

Cetus3D

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.3

Infill:

15%

Notes:

To build one you need to get Neodym magnets of 3x6mm size (4 per tile + 8 for dice tray) like these or these. Print all trays (don't forget to rotate if necessary, print on a flat side) and glue the magnets with super glue in.

Be careful: pay attention to which side you glue magnets to. All tiles have a dot on top - make sure they stick together if oriented the same way.

Update
Added new version of Dice Tray - broken in two parts for those who can't print it in one part. The gap between two parts is 0.2mm. Note that I haven't tested it myself so it might not work for you.

This is a remix of SteveC's nice pinwheel (ThingID: 121959) - traced into SketchUp, cleaned up, made symmetric, and added a handle and bolt. The SketchUp file has been uploaded for anyone wanting to work with the design.

Required: print 1 each of the following pieces: pinwheel, bolt, and handle. Add a 626zz bearing.

Optional: instead of printing the handle, you could print the alternative_handle and add a 3/8" dowel for the handle

Printer settings: solid infill for strength and 0.3mm layers. Also printed successfully in 4 layers at 0.2mm.

  1. Insert a 626zz bearing into the handle (add glue if needed - be careful to keep the bearing able to rotate).
  2. Please note that there is a small lip protruding from the center hole on the pinwheel, and it is meant to be located on the backside of the pinwheel to reduce the amount of pinwheel contacting the bearing. Using a hair dryer on the high setting, heat the plastic of the pinwheel to make it easier to bend the 4 corners up and back onto the center (be careful not to overheat, especially with PLA). Bend it in such a way as to leave about an inch gap over the pinwheel's center hole and below the four corners being folded inward (this allows for more air to be caught into the fins).
  3. Insert bolt into the four corners that have been bent to the center and finally through the center hole on the pinwheel. Then insert the shaft of the bolt into the bearing on the handle. It should be a snug fit but use glue if needed (again, please be careful when applying glue to make sure the bearing still functions).

description.text:
Create your own view-master compatible picture reels!

Say, like if you wanted a disc of your wedding photos or your kids at the park... or even your latest Blender 3D model.

You can customizer this thing for playing around, but generally speaking the generated files and the process below should give you everything you need.

Inspired by: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:28391

1) Print two of the "half_less_film" stl or cut two of the dxf in your paper cutter.

NOTES:
1) You can do the dxf and cut it manually with a hobby knife, so the only printer you really need is an inkjet for the photos!

2) If doing the dxf, you may want to print the captions on the cardstock first.

3) Caption is 90 degrees and above the photo-pair it refers to.

2) Create Photos

Images are a pair of pictures with the camera shifted horizontally 65mm (approx 2 9/16in) between shots.

You can do this with a physical camera, or a virtual camera within a 3D program.

3) Print Photos

Using the svg file in a program like inkscape, scale place all photo pairs in their correct slots.
Place them below the svg layer and the corners will be clipped nicely.

TIPS:
1) Photo pair is exactly 180 to one another, but oriented the SAME DIRECTION.
2) The bottom of each photo should be toward the nearest cog hole.

Print this on transparency film (I have not tested this) and cut around the outside edge with scissors or a hobby knife.

4) Assembly

Glue transparent film wheel between the wheel halves, being careful not to get any on the viewing area.

(I'm guessing cyanoacrylate "super" glue will work.)

description.text:
Martin Tower is a 21-story, 101.2 m (332 ft) skyscraper at 1170 8th Avenue in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania. It is the tallest building in the city, and the greater Lehigh Valley, and 8 ft (2.4 m) taller than the PPL Building in Allentown.

Martin Tower was listed on the National Register of Historic Places on June 28, 2010.

Started in 1969, the framework of the Tower was completed in a short time, but there were insufficient funds to complete the elaborate building and the skeleton of Martin Tower dominated the western horizon of Bethlehem for 2 years before work was resumed. The building was completed and opened in 1972. Bethlehem Steel spared no expense in creating their new skyscraper headquarters. The skyscraper was named after then-Bethlehem Steel chairman Edmund F. Martin.

In 1972, Martin Tower became the new headquarters for Bethlehem Steel. The building was constructed in the shape of a cross (or plus-sign shape) rather than a more conventional square in order to create more corner and window offices. The original offices were designed by decorators from New York and included wooden furniture, doorknobs with the company logo, and handwoven carpets. The building was a testament to the economic heights the Lehigh Valley reached in the 1970s before the large economic turndown caused by the decline of the steel industry. The building was a symbol of Bethlehem Steel's power, money and dominance in the steel industry and an excellent statement of their company. The building has 21 floors and each floor was a different department of the company. When Martin Tower was opened, Bethlehem Steel was the second largest steel producer in the world and the 14th largest industrial corporation in America. In 1973, the first full year the Tower was occupied, Bethlehem Steel set a company record, producing 22.3 million tons of raw steel and shipping 16.3 million tons of finished steel. It made a $207 million profit that year, and exceeded that the following year.

By 1987, the Tower was almost completely vacant as many of the Steel workers had left the Tower due to various reasons. The Tower was then put up for sale and other companies had occupied the Tower and the Annex building. In 2001, Bethlehem Steel filed for bankruptcy and left Martin Tower in 2003. Several companies remained until the last tenant, Receivable Management Services, left the Tower in 2007 leaving it completely vacant.A 2015 video, "Historic Martin Tower", has views of the exterior of the building and portions of the building's campus.

There were also ideas planned by Bethlehem Steel to build a second Tower, which is why some people refer to it as, "Martin Towers." The Annex was going to connect the two Towers but the second one was never built.

The architect for Martin Tower was Haines Lundberg Waehler. It was built by George A. Fuller Construction Co. of New York, which also built the Flat Iron Building in New York in 1903, the CBS Building in New York I 1963 and 1251 Avenue of the Americas at Rockefeller Center in 1971. (Wikipedia)

*This is a scale model

(Photos Curtesy: LehighValleyLive, The Morning Call)

print_settings.Printer:: Geeetech Prusa I3 Dual w/ mods

description.text:
This item is a stand I made a couple years ago. It was designed to hold a specific digital clock and elevate it so the display was easier to read while lying in bed. I doubt many users will be interested in it for the same reason, but it can be scaled and/or cut up, if you have a use for something like this. Scaling the frame in the XY direction will distort the angle of the front edge.

The files consist of one half of the frame and 3 splints that are used to beef-up the two halves that are joined with CA glue. The second half of the stand is made by creating a mirror image of the .STL for left half. The .STL files are scaled up 10 times, except for the single long straight splint, the one that ties the back feet together. They have to be scaled 0.1 to achieve the same size as shown in the photos.

The splint that has an angled edge is designed to fit into the back inside edge of the model; the short straight splint stiffens the glue joint at the front of the stand on the bottom side. The long straight splint ties the frame together at the rear feet of the stand. It was really not needed for my use, and probably doesn't need to be used for most applications.

Printer:

Geeetech Prusa I3 Dual w/ mods

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

I used a 0.4 mm nozzle.

Infill:

as required for your use.

Normal cleanup. It's best to make sure the surfaces that are going to be glued fit together well. Use sand paper to square up any edges that are going to be glued, so the glue forms a strong bond.
I used CA glue to assemble the stand.
After making sure the halves fit together well, I glued the two splints onto half of the frame. Avoid putting too much CA on the splints, so it doesn't run onto the piece that is extended and will be glued to the right half. Let the CA cure before trying to attach the second half. When you are sure the pieces fit together well, add CA to the extended part of the splints and apply a small amount to the frame surfaces that will be joined together.

The splint that ties the two back feet together is opional.

title: Test Tube Holder (for Prusa i3)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a variation of my Test Tube Holder (for Prusa Mendel) thing, which allows you to securely and conveniently mount a test tube to your printer. (I use test tubes to hold ABS juice, which I use to prepare the print bed for prints.)   
This version is modified to fit the Prusa i3 cut from 6.5mm MDF, and it incorporates nut traps so you can use M3 screws to hold the pieces securely in place. Let me know if you need other thicknesses, and I can either change it or get the OpenSCAD file ready for upload.

Print the parts. The two parts in the file hold the test tube pretty securely, but I included a second upper clip in the photo because I already had it printed. I printed with 3 layers top/bottom, two perimeters, and 15% infill.  
Drill out the holes to 3mm and melt a nut into each trap. I used set screws in the photo, but you can also use standard M3 screws.   
Mount the parts onto the side of the printer opposite the X axis motor so you don't limit your Z axis.

This is a game piece I made for the board game Ghosts! Its a fairly easy game to play but I couldn't find the actual board game anywhere unless it was a vintage board game off amazon.

The idea of the game is that neither player knows which of the other player's ghosts are good and which are evil. Facing the front, all ghosts look the same. The dots are only on the back. The players can arrange the good and evil ghosts in any formation they choose at the start of the game.

The game is turn-based. On his or her turn, each player moves one ghost one square, either horizontally or vertically. A ghost may capture an opponent's ghost by moving to its square. Only when a ghost is captured does the opposing player know whether it is good or evil.

If a player captures all four of the opposing player's good ghosts, he or she has won the game. But if a player captures all four of the opposing player's evil ghosts, he or she has lost the game. The game can also be won by moving one of the good ghosts through one of the exits at the opposing side of the board.

The strategy of the game play involves mainly trying to guess which of the opponent's ghosts are which by their movement patterns and trying to fool the opponent with confusing movement patterns.

The game is easy to pick up and fast to play.
You don't need to print the game pieces in different colors but i did it so players can keep better track of their pieces.

The color dot in the back of the ghost piece is to signify which ghost is good or bad. I did this with a small drop of nail polish, but any paint will do.

If you want to make a better game board:

title: V3.0 Scalar - Electronic Box for MEGA/Re-Arm+RAMPS+LCD2004/GLCD+RPI3

description.text:
V3.0

Description

This is the box Version 3.0 of the Ramps + Arduino Mega 2560 / Re-Arm + LCD 2004 RRD / GLCD + Raspberry pi 3
This box was designed for Scalar Family 3D printers.
it will fit 3030 aluminum extrusions and 2020 depending on what part you are printing.

Each part of the box is a separate plastic part.
Print one of each (no special settings required)
Each part can be screwed together using M3x8 screws. Thermoplastic screws are well fit for this kind of application.

Compatibility

This box is compatible with :

  • Ramps 1.4
  • Arduino Mega 2560 or Re-Arm 32Bits
  • RRD LCD2004
  • RRD GLCD
  • 80mm / 60mm fan
  • Raspberry pi 2 / 3

What to Print

Print one of each Stl file and you are ready to go
The naming of each part can tell you if it will fit for 2020 or for 3030 extrusion.
If it's not in the name description then you can print it no matter what extrusion profile you are using.

For 2020 extrusion profiles you need:

  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Left_Grid.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Right_RPI3.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Top_RPI3.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_PT100-60mm-Fan.stl
  • Scalar - ElectronicBox_LCD - Markings.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Base_V2_2020_RPI3.stl
    -Ramps_Box_1.4_Bottom_2020.stl

For 3030 extrusions you need

  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Left_Grid.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Right_RPI3.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Top_RPI3.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_PT100-60mm-Fan.stl
  • Scalar - ElectronicBox_LCD - Markings.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Base_V2_RPI3.stl
  • Ramps_Box_1.4_Bottom.stl

Updates

  • 2018.03.05 - Added Back plate (V2) for 60mm fan + PT100 => changed some holes in order to use thermo screws instead of screws+nuts to attach the 60mm fan.
  • 2017.08.13 - Added some contextual pictures of the box + electronic parts
  • 2017.08.07 - Uploaded missing Bottom parts (both for 3030 and 2020 extrusions)
  • 2017.08.03 : Original post

Your Upgrades/Updates:

  • A top cover for MKS TFT2.8 Touch screen is now available here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2196704
  • (Thanks to http://www.thingiverse.com/warlock4890) Ramps 1.4 Box Side with CAT5 connectors http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1525809

Special notes:

  • Use Thermoplastic screws (M3x8 are great)
  • You can glue each side on the base, it will increased the box rigidity.
  • There are 2 holes available at the bottom of Ramps_Box_1.4_Bottom.stl. (check which version to print 2020 or 3030)
    These holes are dedicated to help you glue this part to the base part:
    Glue the parts together, insert 2 screws, wait a little bit and remove these screws.

f you don't remove these screws after gluing the parts together, the screws will prevent you from properly placing the box on top of the extrusion profile.

This package is compatible with the Scalar Family 3D Printers (Scalar M , Scalar L, Scalar XL, Scalar XLPremium)
The 3D printers kits can be found here:
http://3dmodularsystems.com

How to open .RSDOC

Use Design Spark Mechanical software (free software - Windows only) in order to open the .rsdoc cad files provided.

Have a great printing experience!

print_settings.Notes:: If someone does print this in TPU and the fit isn't 100%, leave a comment, and I can make adjustments for shrinkage or what not.

description.text:
I recently purchased the DEWALT DWA2T35IR Impact Ready FlexTorq Screw Driving Set, 35-Piece. Provided with it was a case, with the normal inserts for all the screwdriver heads. For some reason, the only thing in the case that didn't have it's own insert were the Impact Ready Sockets. They came in a plastic holder that didn't hold up too well.

This piece is for those 4 specific sockets that came with the set. I'm sure you could use it in other Dewalt cases provided they're the same size, but the slots on this item were made for the sizes in the kit (9/16", 1/2", 7/16", & 3/8").

I originally had plans to print this out of TPU, since the normal Dewalt inserts are made of a flexible rubber or plastic, but didn't have enough TPU for this print. I used eSUN PLA+ Pro instead. The fit is tight, but that also helps keep it from falling out. If I do get more TPU, I'll print it out and upload pictures.

I'll also upload the Fusion360 and other formatted source files in case you want to make it shorter/longer or change what size sockets it holds. Here are my notes if you do decide to change the socket size:

EX: The 9/16" socket had an OD of ~19.85mm. Because I planned on using tabs to help it snap in, I used a width of 21mm to give space and allow for shrinkage. You may need to re-distribute the separation and outer lines depending on what sizes you use. Set your rectangle for the needed width, the height should be the same. I cut down 12mm, then filleted the edges until it came out perfectly round (so for the 21mm width, use 10.5mm fillets on both edges). The tabs I put 10mm up from the top/bottom edges. Their dimensions were 4mm x 0.75mm. I extruded them down I believe 2.5mm, then used the draft function to set the angle. The fillets around the edges and tabs may not be necessary, but I prefer designs that way. I'll also leave the sketches (I make no promises that they are clean or make 100% sense :D).

Edit: After publishing I had a small issue closing the case. You have two options here:

  1. Put some extra force to get it set lower in the case, or
  2. Rearrange the other side of the case. The yellow inserts pop out pretty easily, so swap the screwdriver heads for the other attachments. These other attachments sit higher, so the sockets can press against it and make it slightly harder to close.

Cheers!

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select v2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.26

Infill:

55%

Notes:

The first test print I had the wrong dimensions, and the printer had some issues with it. The version that's uploaded is the updated version with a correct fit. If you do use TPU, I'd probably lower the resolution to at least 0.2, and turn the speed down tremendously.

If someone does print this in TPU and the fit isn't 100%, leave a comment, and I can make adjustments for shrinkage or what not.

Robust spool holder for the 1 Kg spools sold by makerbot and others

You will need 25 -35 mm of thread outside the z motor to use this concept. This is a work in progress because I intend to design a different vertical support that launches off the Z motor. You will also need some 0.375 wooden dowels (9.5mm??) The lengths are (2) 213mm for the diagonal piece (2) 180 mm for the vertical piece, and 200 mm for the axle.
If your motors arn't up like mine but are down on the z motor mount than you can make your vertical piece 40 mm shorter and the diagonal piece 46 mm shorter. (calculated not measured)
Print all the parts. The bottom outer goes best with the concavity towards the motor, but it probably doesn't matter. The bottom inner support clamps onto the top threaded rods (theres two parts) Use an epoxy like strong glue to glue the dowels into the plastic wells. The axle parts work thusly. The thinner part with a cone fits the side if the spool withoout a center well. The bigger part fits into the well. Space the parts so that the spool center hole is suspended on the inner smaller diameter hub. 
I've attached a photo of the axle. The dowel is long so as to make a handle. The holder can go above either motor and there is no reason why you can't have two installed, just mirror the axle assembly (not the plastic)
I acknowledge SSW's Thing-O-Matic Filament Spool Bracket as the inspiration for this, I build 2 of his thing for my TOM, but with the improved axle.
I have included the Alibre files and STEP versions in the zip file.

title: Iphone 7 Case w/ Heart Bumpers v3.5

description.text:
This is an Iphone 6, 6s & 7 compatible case.

Similar to my other Iphone case this one has bumpers but the are Hearts instead of lines. If you use ABS or PETG it will be strong enough to leave in the car in the summer & not melt. I also updated the camera hole to be a little more snug, let me know what you guys think in the comments!

I have had it on my phone now for 3-4 weeks and it has held up great and it has been dropped several times & survived unscathed.

I printed it with PETG (For the heat & Strength properties) at 0.1mm Layer height with supports for the bumpers. If you wanted it a little stronger you could print it @ 0.2mm layer height but you might lose some detail.

Happy Printing everyone!

title: Fan Holder for Costume Glove Dryer

description.text:
Costumes often have gloves and they tend to get sweaty - this is especially an issue with fursuit hands. A dryer is simple to build: just get two short pieces of 40mm sewer pipe, two 12V fans that ideally still run on 5V so you can use an USB charger or battery, and something to attach the fans to the pipes. Before I had a 3D printer it looked like this, but I couldn't find the fans last night and there's a convention coming up next week. With the printer the answer to all questions seems to be PLA, so I quickly created this holder. The most time consuming task is soldering the electrical connections by the way.

The holder is intended to be a tight fit - hence no holes to fasten the fan. You may need to file the sockets for the tube and the fan to fit your equipment, especially the outer dimensions of the fan vary from model to model. Since the fans I took from my "oh I can use that again" box are 15 mm high the holder will accept these.

Though this is more an illustration on how this particular task can be done I've added the FreeCAD file for easy modification and remix. The grill shown in one of the photos is one by capitaenz

BTW, Slice3r creates supports that are difficult or impossible to remove, Cura creates better results.

http://youtu.be/omsI9QdFpDc

i use cura and printed on normal settings. nothing fancy. printed in PLA.

Simple thrust meter for measuring propeller efficiency and maximum thrust.

While the existing thrust meter here on thingyverse may be more stable and accurate than my design, they are large and therefore require much material and storage space later (which I don't have).

So I've thrown this 3 piece thrust meter together for quick prop comparison.

Like all of my designs it needs a low amount of filament (20g)
The base simply slides on this scale (use electrical tape if it is slightly loose):
https://www.banggood.com/2000g-x-0_1g-Electronic-Balanc-p-980101.html?p=C8021898693762017049

Speed controller:
https://www.banggood.com/Wholesale-EK2-0907-Updated-Version-Servo-Tester-Server-Electronic-Speed-Controller-p-66240.html?p=C8021898693762017049

description.text:
Saw this on the Tevo Facebook group but when I loaded the stl that was posted it was malformed so I knocked this up in 5 minutes in Fusion 360. I'd credit him/her but the name was Chinese characters and I don't speak Chinese. Google came up with Elsa so we'll go with that, thanks Elsa for the design.

It spins with the extruder easily showing when it is feeding and when it's retracting. Could even be used for some sort of calibration.
Push fit for a 5mm stepper shaft.

I've taken Elsa's design a bit further by adding a dial face with 5 degree markings that attaches to the stepper motor screws. I haven't tested it but the holes are measured to fit a standard stepper motor.

A drill press for use with a JOOLTOOL Flex-Shaft (http://jooltool.com/site/product/flex-shaft-drilling-kit/). Designed with PCB fabrication in mind, but can be used on other materials including plastics and aluminum. Video:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FTrcmPRxDG8&feature=youtu.be This design has been refined since the above photos and video were taken.

For this press, aside from the 3D printed components hosted here on Thingiverse, you will need:
  • JOOLTOOL Flex Shaft Kit (http://jooltool.com/site/product/flex-shaft-drilling-kit/)
  • 10mm smooth rod
  • 10mm linear bearings (x2)
  • large spring
  • 0.5" x 0.125" Aluminum bar stock (for the levers)
  • 8-32 nuts and bolts (for lever joints, mounting, and clamps)
  • 10-32 bolt and nut (for z-adjust)
  • 8-32 tap (for joining the two levers)
  • washers (optional)
  • small woodscrews (for mounting the base cover plate)
  • plasti-dip (optional - for the lever handle)
  • concrete patch (for filling the base)
    • More details on this build here:
    http://bryancera.blogspot.com/2014/02/diy-drill-press.html

description.text:
Hi guys- when I saw the amazing working ocarina on the front page, I made it my duty to put a triforce on it and make the Ocarina of Time! All credit of course goes to seggybop for the original design.
I also included the openscad file and triforce I designed if anyone wants to play around with the placement.
If you want to learn some zelda songs to play on it, try these finger guides:
http://www.smule.com/songbook/scores/tagged/52

Please follow seggybop's instructions here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:234512/#instructions
When printing this and the original ocarina, I found that a coat of silicone caulking on the inside of both halves is great for improving the sound of the final product.
The triforce is raised and so should be easy to paint gold if you want it to look like the real thing. a coating of polyurethane or silicone will make painting easier.

description.text:
I wanted to make a spinner that had interchangeable arms. So I did. You can have a different body and arm color. The idea was that if you made them for kids, they could trade and upgrade the arms with new ones and have whatever color scheme they like.

Use pennies for the weights. Tip: Use a gram scale or a balance for your sets of pennies to make sure they are very close to the same weight in each arm to get proper balance. Or only use all pennies from the same year or something. The metal composition has changes many times over the years, so they have a pretty large variance in weight.

Notes:

There's only 1 body design, but 3 different arms are included. The number in the filename like ".01mm" denotes the offset between the dovetail joint in the arm and on the body. I made 3 versions, should accommodate different printers while keeping the size of the holes for the bearings and pennies the correct size.
You may still have to scale body or arm a little to get a tight fit.

title: Dial Indicator mount for Anet A8

description.text:
This is a little mount I made for attaching a dial indicator to the print head of an Anet A8. its not perfect, but it works for me. The bore of the mount fits a gauge with a shaft diameter of about 8mm, and the little screw i use for clamping the gauge in place is a spare left over from the xyz stop switches, a little 2mm self tapping screw.
The STL i uploaded is slightly different (improved hopefully) from the one pictured. It has deeper mount screw holes to allow for the fan shield and I made it a little large to support the gauge a little more robustly.
The way I use it is as follows. Set your Z-Offset, then level your bed. Use as many points on the bed as you see fit ( my bed is concave a little so I measure near the corners and leave it at that). Once your bed is level re-check your Z-offset , and away you go.
If you like it and have any suggestions on how it might be improved Im all ears.

print_settings.Notes:: When I put my model into Cura I scaled it up to 110% but then dropped the Z to 105% but in hindsight you may be better with leaving it at 110% or possibly scaling it up anywhere up to 120%. With the 105% Z setting it is 4.2 mm tall and semi flimsy but still stable, when crashing instead of chipping like other models on Thingiverse, this boomerang bends and absorbs much of the shock. I suggest when you print this make several shells I think mine had something like 10, this will increase its durability significantly, the more shells the better.
print_settings.Printer:: R1 ABS + PLA Model

description.text:
I will be updating this soon to include a model that is for intermediate throwers with wider and slightly thicker wings.

This was my second attempt at a 4 winged boomerang. This is a most definitely expert level boomerang and is thrown slightly atypically. rather than a typical 80-70 degree throw you should try a lofty throw with around a 45 degree throw or higher. Never the less this boomerang actually comes back with a little bit of getting used to I assure you, I just caught it only by moving a few steps about 10x in a row.

This is a righty boomerang, mirror it in the slicer for an easy lefty make.

This boomerang is an extreme carver and if you are finding that it arcs up high at the turn around you should try to push the tapered edge down with your pointer finger whilst simultaneously pushing up the flat edge with your thumb. Then run this the whole length for each wing and when you pull away you should notice the boomerang wing tips are now slightly below the center. This should mediate your problem as well as allow this boomerang to be thrown at an angle closer to normal.

I get into this later but this model is very shock absorbent upon crashing, even when made with PLA. I suggest ABS for this but PLA will still work all the same, just not as durable, but I made mine with PLA.

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

First you obviously have to flip it 90 degrees in the slicer so its flat, I'm not sure why the part is upright.

When I put my model into Cura I scaled it up to 110% but then dropped the Z to 105% but in hindsight you may be better with leaving it at 110% or possibly scaling it up anywhere up to 120%. With the 105% Z setting it is 4.2 mm tall and semi flimsy but still stable, when crashing instead of chipping like other models on Thingiverse, this boomerang bends and absorbs much of the shock. I suggest when you print this make several shells I think mine had something like 10, this will increase its durability significantly, the more shells the better.
I made this as a first time in Fusion 360 project using (genraly) a sweep and a pattern>circle approach since you pretty much can't chamfer a arc (and it took me way too long to realize that).

description.text:
Geared fidget spinner based off of several other designs I've seen, I'm not sure where it originated from. The bearings are linked so spinning the case around the central bearing spins the outer bearings and vice versa. This one uses magnetic gears instead of traditional gears.

Parts:
Uses 48 - 4x2 magnets* on the gears, more if you also use them to hold the parts together (or you can use glue dots*. The magnets on the gears alternate between north and south facing out.

Needs 5 - skate bearings* (there are two in the center). It'll probably work better with ceramic ball / magnetic steel bearings*, but I used normal metal bearings (which are affected by the magnets and only spins for a few seconds).

Filament:
Atomic Filament Starry Night PLA and Filamentum Vertigo Gray* and Rapunzel Silver* PLA.

*affiliate links

Supports:

Yes

Print the top and bottom then using a 4 x4 inch solar film between them attach the bottom and top with 8 M3 10mm screws (Do not use flat head screws unless you add the counter sink to the model).

Trim the excess solar film with a hobby knife for a cleaner look.

The top ring has a square recess to help align the solar film, use double sided tab to hold it in place before attaching bottom ring. Make sure to follow the direction on the solar film as to what side face the sun (normally the silver side)

This is filter is 10mm thick, much thicker then it really needs to be but i only have 10mm screw on hand and did not want them to extruding out.

Never look directly at the sun with out a working solar filter. Inspect solar filter film befor each use for damage and replace as needed.
